{{distinguish|Bainport (Netherlands)}} {{Use dmy dates|date=September 2013}} '''BrainPort''' is a technology whereby sensory information can be sent to one's brain through an electrode array which sits atop the tongue.<ref name="WicabTrumanIndex">{{cite journal | last1 = Prather | first1 = Laura | date = 15 February 2007 | title = Tongue creates sight for blind: Visually impaired persons will be able to use device to sense images on tongue | journal = [[Truman State University Index]] | volume = 98 | issue = 20 | pages = 11 | url = http://index.truman.edu/pdfarchive/Feb152007.pdf |format=PDF| accessdate = 2009-05-24 }}</ref> It was initially developed by [[Paul Bach-y-Rita]] as an aid to people's [[Senses#Balance and acceleration|sense of balance]], particularly of [[stroke]] victims. Bach-y-Rita founded ''Wicab'' in 1998.<ref>[http://wicab.com/ Wicab] retrieved 4 October 2009</ref><ref>[https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2007/11/071107210356.htm Article briefly discusses the use of the BrainPort as a balance aid for stroke victims.]</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://mindstates.tribe.net/thread/a8b9f33f-7a6f-4af8-9c0c-588719606271# |title=BrainPort, Dr. Paul Bach-y-Rita, and Sensory Substitution, 23 November 2004 |access-date=4 October 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100429004238/http://mindstates.tribe.net/thread/a8b9f33f-7a6f-4af8-9c0c-588719606271# |archive-date=29 April 2010 |dead-url=yes |df=dmy-all }}</ref>
It has also been developed for use as a visual aid, demonstrating its ability to allow a blind person to see his or her surroundings in polygonal and pixel form. In this scenario, a camera picks up the image of the surrounding, the information is processed by a chip which converts it into impulses which are sent through an electrode array, via the tongue, to the person's brain. The human brain is able to interpret these impulses as visual signals and they are then redirected to the visual cortex, allowing the person to "see." This is similar in part to how a [[cochlear implant]] works, in that it transmits electrical stimuli to a receiving device in the body. <ref>[http://science.howstuffworks.com/brainport.htm How Stuff Works: How BrainPort works] retrieved 4 October 2009</ref> <ref>[http://discovermagazine.com/2003/jun/feattongue Can you see with your tongue?] ''Discover Magazine'' published 1 June 2003</ref>
The BrainPort V100 oral electronic vision aid was approved by the Food and Drug Administration (FDA) on June 18, 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Press Announcements - FDA allows marketing of new device to help the blind process visual signals via their tongues|url = http://www.fda.gov/NewsEvents/Newsroom/PressAnnouncements/ucm451779.htm|website = www.fda.gov|access-date = 2016-02-14|language = en}}</ref>
