{{Infobox company | name = Embrace | logo = | type = [[Non-profit organization]] | foundation = 2008 | location = [[San Francisco, California]], [[United States]] | key_people = * [[Jane Chen]] (Co-Founder) * [[Linus Liang]] (Co-Founder) * [[Rahul Panicker]] (Co-Founder) * Naganand Murty (Co-Founder) * [[Razmig Hovaghimian]] (Co-Founder) | industry = [[Health Care]] | homepage = [http://www.embraceglobal.org/ www.embraceglobal.org] }}
'''Embrace''' is a [[non profit]] organization providing low-cost incubators to prevent neonatal deaths in rural areas in developing countries.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://extreme.stanford.edu/big_picture/our_class.html |publisher=Stanford Institute of Design |title=Entrepreneurial Design For Extreme Affordability |accessdate=2008-09-14 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080915185523/http://extreme.stanford.edu/big_picture/our_class.html |archivedate=2008-09-15 |df= }}</ref> The organization was developed in 2008 during the multidisciplinary Entrepreneurial Design For Extreme Affordability course at [[Stanford University]] by group members [[Jane Chen]], [[Linus Liang]], [[Rahul Panicker]], [[Razmig Hovaghimian]], and Naganand Murty.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://ngm.nationalgeographic.com/big-idea/16/little-packages |title=Big Ideas, little packages |publisher=National Geographic}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Lee|first=Ellen|title=Embrace may keep babies warm - and alive|url=http://www.sfgate.com/business/article/Embrace-may-keep-babies-warm-and-alive-3166256.php|accessdate=19 July 2012|newspaper=SFGate|date=2010-11-12}}</ref>
In 2015 Embrace became part of [[East Meets West (non-governmental organization)|Thrive Networks]] (also called East Meets West) which is a non-governmental organization founded in 1988 by [[Le Ly Hayslip]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://thrivenetworks.org/about-us/history/|title=History {{!}} Thrive Networks|website=Thrive Networks|language=en-US|access-date=2016-07-13}}</ref> Thrive Networks focuses on areas such as health, water, sanitation, and education in various countries throughout the world.
==Incubator== The Embrace infant warmer is a low-cost solution that maintains premature and low-birth-weight babies’ body temperature, that would give premature infants a better chance at survival. A baby born two weeks premature lacks the ability to regulate its own body temperature. The child will likely die if not transferred to an incubator within an hour. With the Embrace Warmer, which is a specially designed polymer blanket, that vital time span becomes 4 hours.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://bigthink.com/think-tank/a-place-where-makers-can-pursue-their-dreams-with-techshops-mark-hatch|title=A Place Where Makers Can Pursue Their Dreams, with TechShop's Mark Hatch|last=Editors|first=Big Think (Over a year ago)|date=|work=Big Think|access-date=2017-07-27}}</ref> The infant warmer is portable, safe, reusable, and requires only intermittent access to electricity.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://sanjose.bizjournals.com/sanjose/stories/2008/04/21/story10.html?b=1208750400^1622061&surround=etf | title = Stanford startup's $25 'sleeping bag' could save newborns | accessdate = 2008-09-14 | date = 2008-04-18 | first=Lisa | last=Sibley}}</ref> Each baby warmer is priced at approximately $25.<ref>{{cite news|last=Kannani|first=Rahim|title=Investing in Women and Girls: A Focus on Health, Advocacy and Innovation|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/rahim-kanani/investing-in-women-and-gi_b_589043.html|accessdate=19 July 2012|newspaper=Huffington Post|date=2010-05-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Moore |first=Thomas |url=http://news.sky.com/story/824845/low-tech-body-warmer-is-a-baby-life-saver |title=Low tech body warmer is a baby life saver |accessdate=19 July 2012 |newspaper=Sky News |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120905150328/http://news.sky.com/story/824845/low-tech-body-warmer-is-a-baby-life-saver |archivedate=5 September 2012 |df= }}</ref> The Embrace development team won the fellowship at the [[Echoing Green]] competition in 2008 for this concept.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://thinkchangeindia.wordpress.com/2008/09/04/extreme-affordability/ |title= ThinkChange India: Extreme Affordability |accessdate= 2008-09-14 |date= 2008-09-04 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.echoinggreen.org/fellows/jane-chen-and-rahul-panicker |title= Jane Chen and Rahul Panicker |accessdate= 2008-09-14 }}</ref> Embrace also won the 2007-2008 [[Business Association of Stanford Entrepreneurial Students]] Social E-Challenge competition grand prize.{{Citation needed|date=July 2012}} At a ceremony at BAFTA in London on December 3rd 2013 [[Jane Chen]], [[Linus Liang]], Naganand Murty and [[Rahul Panicker]] won an innovation award from the Economist.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.economist.com/news/technology-quarterly/21590752-innovation-awards-our-annual-prizes-recognise-successful-innovators-eight |title= Technology Quarterly Q4 2013: And the winners are |accessdate= 2013-12-02 | work=The Economist |date=2013-11-30}}</ref> Embrace also partners with [[UniversalGiving]] to raise fund for its project, which is to provide the Embrace infant warmers in Kabul, Afghanistan.
