{{Infobox NRHP | name = Nellie Johnstone No. 1 | nrhp_type = | image = Nellie Johnstone No. 1.JPG | caption = Replica of Nellie Johnstone No. 1 drilling rig in Bartlesville, Oklahoma. Photo taken September 29, 2013 | location= Johnstone Park, [[Bartlesville, Oklahoma]] | coordinates = {{coord|36|45|23|N|95|58|19|W|display=inline,title}} | locmapin = Oklahoma#USA | map_label = Nellie Johnstone No. 1 | map_caption = Location in [[Oklahoma]]##Location in [[United States]] | built = {{Start date|1897}} | builder = Cudahy Oil Co. | architecture = | added = April 11, 1972 | area = {{convert|10|acre}} | governing_body = Local | refnum = 72001077<ref name="nris">{{NRISref|version=2010a}}</ref> }}
'''Nellie Johnstone No. 1''' was the first commercially productive oil well in [[Oklahoma]] (at that time in [[Indian Territory]]). Completed on April 15, 1897, the well was drilled in the Bartlesville Sand near [[Bartlesville, Oklahoma|Bartlesville]], opening an era of oil exploration and development in Oklahoma. It was abandoned as a well in 1964. The site was donated to the city of Bartlesville and is now a park, listed on the National Register of Historic Places, featuring a restored drilling rig.<ref name=nrhpinv1>{{cite web|last=Ruth|first=Kent|title=National Register of Historic Places Inventory - Nomination Form: Nellie Johnstone No. 1|url={{NRHP url|id=72001077}}|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=9 May 2013|date=September 1971}}</ref>
==Background== The well was backed by George B. Keeler and William Johnstone,{{efn|Keeler and Johnstone were young men initially hired by [[Jacob Bartles]] (namesake of the community of Bartlesville) to work in Bartles' general store.}} Keeler had been adopted into the Osage Nation and Johnstone had been adopted into the Delaware Nation after marrying Native American women. Keeler and Johnstone left Bartles to open their own store near the Osage Indian Agency on the [[Caney River]], and was named for Johnstone's daughter. Keeler and Johnstone, together with partner Frank Overlees and their Native American wives, leased {{convert|200000|acres|km2}} from the [[Cherokee Nation]] on an area of [[oil seep]] and engaged the Cudahy Oil Company to finance the actual drilling operation.<ref name="aoghs">[https://aoghs.org/petroleum-pioneers/first-oklahoma-oil-well/ "First Oklahoma Oil Well." American Oil & Gas Historical Society.] Accessed October 20, 2017.</ref>{{efn|Cudahy Oil Company was owned by businessman Michael Cudahy of Chicago, who is better known as a member of the family that created the Cudahy Meat Packing empire.<ref name="aoghs"/>}}
==Organizing and drilling== The firm of McBride and Bloom, headquartered in Independence, Kansas, had already been drilling in the Red Fork field. The original drilling rig had been used at a [[wikt:dry hole|dry hole]] near Sapulpa. It took two weeks to move it by oxcart {{convert|70|miles|km}} overland to the Bartlesville site. The well went to {{convert|1320|ft|m}}, and was completed using a then-usual technique of placing a "torpedo" (containing a liquid nitroglycerine charge) into the well to fracture the bore and release the oil. Keeler's stepdaughter, Jennie Cass, dropped the "go devil" charge,{{efn|Dictionary.com defines go-devil in this context as "...a dart dropped into a well, especially an oil well, to explode a charge of dynamite or nitroglycerine previously placed in a desired position."<ref>[http://www.dictionary.com/browse/go-devil go-devil dictionary.com. "go-devil" (def. 2).] Accessed October 20, 2017.</ref>}} causing the explosive to detonate on impact, in front of fifty spectators.{{efn|This process was called "shooting the well."<ref name="aoghs"/>}} The ensuing gusher produced between 50 and 75 barrels a day, and had to be capped for two years until means could be found to move the oil to a more distant market.<ref name=eoh1>{{cite web|last=Wilson|first=Linda D.|title=Nellie Johnstone Number One a|url=http://digital.library.okstate.edu/encyclopedia/entries/N/NE003.html|publisher=Oklahoma Historical Society|accessdate=10 May 2013}}</ref><ref name=aoghs1>{{cite web|title=Discovering Oklahoma Oil|url=http://aoghs.org/technology/first-oklahoma-oil-well/|publisher=American Oil & Gas Historical Society|accessdate=10 May 2013}}</ref>
According to Kenny Franks' article in the ''Encyclopedia of Oklahoma History & Culture'', the Nellie Johnstone well had not been properly sealed before it was capped. Oil continued seeping into the sump while the well was blocked, eventually overflowing into the nearby [[Caney River]]. During the unusually cold winter that followed, a group of children ice skating on the frozen river, built a bonfire to keep themselves warm. Somehow the fire spread close to the oil seep, igniting it. The fire then spread to the Nellie Johnstone, causing major damage to the facility.<ref name="EOHC-Franks">[http://www.okhistory.org/publications/enc/entry.php?entry=pe023 Franks, Kenny A. "Petroleum Industry." ''Encyclopedia of Oklahoma History & Culture''.] Accessed October 20, 2017.</ref>
The well was uncapped in 1900, after the Kansas, Oklahoma Central and Southwestern Railway, later acquired by [[Atchison, Topeka and Santa Fe Railroad]], came to Bartlesville, stimulating the development of the Bartlesville field by offering to transport crude to market in [[Neodesha, Kansas]]. {{efn|The well produced more than {{convert|100|koilbbl}} of oil in its lifetime, before it was capped in 1948.<ref name=eoh1/>}} Nellie Johnstone Cannon, who was six years old at the time the well was drilled and named for her, was granted the land on which the well was drilled by allotment through her Native American ancestry.{{efn|Nellie Johnstone Cannon was a descendant of Delaware chief Charles Journeycake.<ref name=eoh1/>}} She sold the land to Bartlesville in 1917. The area is now Johnstone Park.
==Creation of Johnstone Park== A replica drilling rig was built over the well in 1948, while the rig was still producing. After the Johnstone No. 1 well was abandoned in 1963, and interest in maintaining the site as a historical monument had begun to grow, the rig scene was reconstructed, using redwood timbers for the derrick.<ref name=eoh1/> The derrick was rebuilt in 2008.<ref name=aoghs1/>
The well site was listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 1972.<ref name="nris"/>
